photo.description: Bookplate (with motto: Fortis in arduis) of James Wyllie Guild (1826-1894), Scottish public accountant and antiquarian. The son of a solicitor, he was born in Arbroath, Scotland, and educated at the Royal High School in Edinburgh. A founding member of the Institute of Accountants and Actuaries in Glasgow (IAAG), he served as its secretary (1867-1873), president (1873-1881), and treasurer (1881-1894). In 1851 he married Clarissa Finlay, with whom he had ten children. Over 3000 items from his library and antiquarian collections were sold at auction in April 1888; cf. Catalogue of the Valuable Library of J. Wyllie Guild ... (Edinburgh: Chapman, 1888). For his biography, see his entry in T.A. Lee, Seekers of Truth: The Scottish Founders of Modern Public Accountancy (Oxford: JAI Press, 2006). Established heading: Guild, James Wyllie Penn Libraries call number: Inc T-372 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Bookplate of George Dunn (1864-1912), English bibliographer and book collector. From his obituary: On Tuesday of last week there died suddenly from pneumonia, at the age of forty-seven, a man whose remarkable gifts and attainments deserve more than the few paragraphs of record that have appeared in the public press. Mr. George Dunn, of Woolley Hall, near Maidenhead, was a member of a well-known Northumbrian Catholic family. He was educated at Beaumont College, Windsor, and at Stonyhurst, and was afterwards called to the Bar, though he never practised as a barrister. Inheriting from his father, the late George Dunn, of Bath House, Newcastle, large estates both in Northumberland and Berkshire, together with sufficient revenues, he was able to indulge the tastes of a scholar and collector of early printed books, mediaeval bindings, manuscripts, old silver, and old clocks, as well as those of a sportsman and keen angler, an astronomer and a student of forestry. Of none of these things was he content to have a superficial knowledge. Indeed, it may be said that he handled nothing without mastering it completely ... With these and other interests and pursuits George Dunn lived a tranquil and sequestered life, unmarried and alone in a large house, where he occasionally entertained one or other of the small band of intimates to whom he was devoted and by whom he was beloved. Neatly dressed, shy, spare, and rather below the middle height, he might sometimes be seen entering the British Museum or the Bodleian Library, or quietly turning over the book-treasures in the London sale rooms. But he never attended meetings or went into society, or gave the smallest encouragement to mere acquaintances. He was a Conservative in politics, a model landlord, and a loyal son of the Catholic Church. -- "Mr. George Dunn," The Times (11 March 1912), p. 11, issue 39843, col C. photo.description: petrus sutoris septem Ingenuarum artium magister Iuris su[m]mi ponti ficis bac[caulaureus] [Autograph of Petrus Sutoris. According to the bookseller's description of this work, he is to be identified with "the Sorbonne theologian and Carthusian monk, Petrus Sutor (Pierre Cousturier, ca. 1475-1537), who was involved in bitter controversies with Erasmus" (E.K Schreiber, catalogue 20, no. 5). If that is so, this inscription should be dated prior to 1510, when Cousturier received his doctorate in theology (he entered the Carthusian order in 1511). It might possibly date to the period when he was teaching at the Collège de Sainte-Barbe, ca. 1495-ca. 1502 (the work in which it appears is dated ca. 1498-1500). Cf. P.G. Bietenholz and T.B. Deutscher, eds., Contemporaries of Erasmus v. 1 (Toronto: U of Toronto Press, 1985), p. 352. According to Bietenholz and Deutscher, Cousturier "oppose[d] the reformist goals and methods advocated by the humanists, whom Cousturier saw as radical and even heretical reformers" (ibid.). Established heading: Cousturier, Pierre 1475?-1537] Penn Libraries call number: Inc S-444 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Partially illegible 16th-century Latin poem (dated 1568) by and in the hand of Peter Satlpoger. The Satlpoger (or Sattelbogen or Satlboger) family was an influential noble clan in the Bavarian Forest from the tenth through the sixteenth centuries. Anno 1568 A me Petro Satlpoger Composita O Deus humane [...]es Vnita & op[...] turb[a]e. D[omi]ni sine fine manes principio[que] [...] Non auerte tuos quibus omnia cer[...] ocellos. Sed me a cunctis protege que so in Respice me miserum coeli fabricat[...] orbis Tu solus famulum pace beari pote[...] O Deus o rerum Pater o rex inclite Christe Fac tibi sincero corde placere que a m[...] Vt[que] tibi toto possim residere [...] Et fac ne scuo pr[...]s[...] ab [...] [...] [...] Penn Libraries call number: Inc S-311 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Ex Bibliotheca aulica R[everen]d[issi]mi & Ill[ustrissi]mi Principis Elvacensis Ownership inscription of the court library of the Fürstpropstei Ellwangen (or, Bibliotheca Elvacensis, Ellwanger Hofbibliothek, Bibliotheca Aulica Elvacensis). This was the court library of the Fürstpropstei Ellwangen (English article here). Originally founded as a Benedictine monastery in the eighth century and raised to the eminence of a Reichsabtei in the ninth, the original Stift Ellwangen had by the early 15th century declined to the point that the Benedictines abandoned it. In 1460 the foundation was given over to a college of secular (Augustinian) canons presided over by a Fürstpropst (prince-provost), who ruled not only the college itself but a small principality centered on the city of Ellwangen (near the eastern border of what is now Baden-Württemberg). The library was a later development, its volumes acquired during the 17th and 18th centuries as the prince-provost's private collection. The college was secularized in 1802; the library was dissolved in 1806, most of the books remaining in Ellwangen to form the basis of the collection of the short-lived Katholisch-Theologische Friedrichs-Universität Ellwangen (1812-1817), subsequently absorbed into the Universität Tübingen as its theological faculty (cf. H. Hummel, ed., Katalog der Inkunabeln in Bibliotheken der Diözese Rottenburg-Stuttgart (Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz, 1993), p. 290). DNB heading: Stift Ellwangen Penn Libraries call number: Inc P-486 Folio All images from this book

photo.description: Boninus Mombritius Mediolanensis, hoc eodem tempore 1460 sub typographia [...] initium floruisse crediter .... multo annos in colligendis sanctorum Aelis[?] post anum [sic] 1460. inscripsisse videtur, quo typographia in usum litteratorum [...]it, ut ingentia duo volumina orbi oss[...] Inscribuntur Vit[a]e et Acta Sanctorum collecta et edita per Boninum Mombritium Mediolanensem. Vetus editio duobus volum. fol. Cum autem ubique nota temporis et loci h[a]ec impressa sint, hinc su[...]tes typo- graphi[a]e initium Mediolani vel alibi prodi[...] inter annum 1470 et 1480 visi harum rerum erudite con- jiciunt. De hac collectione insigni mentionem honorificari facit Joannes Bollandus Societatis Jesu in prefatione generali ad vitas sanctorum cap. 1. pag. 5. pag. [...] hisce [...]bis Boninus Mombritius Medio- "lanensis duo ingentia volumina edidit, quibis acta sanctorum completus est ut ea in MSS. codicibus se- "perit ita fideliter, ut ne [...]da quidam scriptiones correxerit, qu[a]e minus jucundam lectionem red- "dere solent. Dicavit illlud [...] quo sanctissimum inscripsit honestissimo Equite Cicho Simonet[a]e [...] "Mediolanensium secretario. H[a]ec Bollandus. Multa quoque alia opuscula composuisse legitur qu[a]e adhuc MSS. in bibliothecis extant. In Philippi Labbei Bibliotheca MSS. librorum hoc specimine an- tiquarum lectionem Gr[a]ecorum. Parisiis in 4o an. 1653 apud Joannem Henault ex MSS. codicibus Regi[a]e Galliarum Bibliothec[a]e potissimum collecta, ibidem in supplemento VIII quo [blank space] qu[a]edam ex catalogo MSS. codicum, qui continentur in 2a parte h[...] [blank space] bibliothec[a]e Regi[a]e, et in fascicules li brorum nondum compactis pag. 3 [blank space] Codice DCLXIX Bonini Mombritie de Varietate Fortun[a]e ad Galeatium Sfortiam Mediolani Ducum Ibidem pag. 305. Codice MLVIII Bonini Mombritie Poe- ma de nuptiis Tristian Vicecomitis. H[a]ec de MSS. nondum editis reciso[?] licuit latuitibus in Regia Galliarum Bibliotheca. Vixit autem usque ad annum 1496 Mombritius, quo edendum procusavit[?] Glossasicem[?] Papi[a]e Gramaticum, quod prefectum Venetiis in fol. anno dicto MCCCCXCVI die 19 men- sis aprilis. cujus ni fidem facit Carolus du Fresne Dominus du Conge ad Gloss[...]icem Medi[a]e et Jutim[a]e Latinitatis paragr. 44 pag. 36 Oudinus de scriptoribus Euleisi[a]e antiquis Tom. 3o pag. 265q. collegit ex quatuor Evangelistis hexametro casncine[?] Dominic[a]e Passionis ad Sixtum IV. S.M. libros sex, quorum initium est. Qui nineis[?] absunpsi primos juveniliter annos Michael a S. Josepho in Bibliographia Critica titulo Boninus [...] [...] Orlandi nel suo trattati dell' origine e progresso della stampa crede[?] il Mombrizio stampato in Milano i anno 1476. in circa nella Stamperia del Zaroni. photo.description: Armorial bookplate of George Dawson Coleman (1825-1878), American ironmaster, politician and philanthropist. Grandson of Robert Coleman, Pennsylvania's first millionaire, he studied at Princeton and received his A.M. from Penn in 1843. With his brother, Robert Coleman, he ran the family iron business (cf. Cornwall Iron Furnace) until Robert's retirement in 1857, after which he continued in sole charge until his death. In 1852 he married Deborah Brown (a scion of the Norris family through her mother) and had 13 children, 6 of whom survived to adulthood. Coleman served in the Pennsylvania General Assembly and Senate and was a founding member of the Pennsylvania State Board of Charities. Cf. his entry in J.W. Jordan, Encyclopedia of Pennsylvania Biography, v. 1 (New York: Lewis Historical Pub. Co., 1914). Penn Libraries call number: Inc M-499 Folio All images from this book
